A defiant President Biden on Monday said he did not regret his decision to withdraw American forces from Afghanistan, while acknowledging that the country's collapse to the Taliban came much sooner than U.S. officials had anticipated.

"I stand squarely behind my decision," he said from the White House. "The truth is this did unfold more quickly than we had anticipated.”

node.text:
Time is not on Trump's side. The Biden administration saw a major win by passing a bipartisan trillion dollar infrastructure bill that could flood the workforce with thousands of jobs and keep his campaign promise to fix Washington. Since losing the 2020 election, the former president has had a handful of botched attempts to return to the spotlight. 

Ryan Lizza breaks down the dynamics of Trump's return, what's working, what isn't and what to expect next.

node.title: Trump's influence keeps haunting Washington, explained

node.text:
A year after New York Gov. Andrew Cuomo reached new political heights with daily news briefings that enraptured a nation in the throes of a once-in-a-lifetime pandemic, the three-term Democrat announced plans to resign amid growing pressure to leave or face impeachment over allegations that he sexually harassed nearly a dozen women.

“Given the circumstances, the best way I can help now is if I step aside and let the government get back to government,” Cuomo said in a video statement. “Therefore that's what I'll do, because I work for you, and doing the right thing, is doing the right thing for you. Because, as we say, ‘it's not about me, it's about we.’” 

Read more at the link in bio.

https://politi.co/2UaCHK6

node.title: Andrew Cuomo resigns amid sexual harassment scandal

node.text:
Say goodbye to one of America's most recognizable Confederate monuments. Richmond, Virginia's 21-foot statue of Robert E. Lee will be taken down tomorrow as a symbol of racial injustice, more than 130 years after it was erected in tribute to the South’s Civil War leader.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Gov. Ralph Northam originally announced plans to take down the statue in June 2020, 10 days after George Floyd's death sparked nationwide protests against police brutality and racism. But despite months of protests (swipe 👈), Northam's plans were stalled for more than a year by two lawsuits filed by residents opposed to its removal. Last week, rulings by the Supreme Court of Virginia cleared the way for the statue to be taken down.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Richmond was the capital of the Confederacy for much of the Civil War. The city has removed more than a dozen other Confederate symbols on city land since Floyd’s death. Link in bio for more.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
📷 AP, Getty

Donald Trump is signaling a heightened interest in a rematch with Joe Biden — and laying the necessary groundwork.

Since his November defeat, Trump has suggested that he will seek a rematch in 2024. That’s nothing new. But associates say Biden’s declining political favor amid a Covid resurgence and the Aug.15 fall of Kabul have intensified the interest of the former president. 

Trump's operation is taking concrete steps to enhance his profile and position him for a potential campaign. Several rallies have been added recently to Trump’s fall schedule. There are plans for events in the first-in-the-nation presidential state of Iowa and the critical swing state of Florida. His fundraising picked up this year as he raised $82 million in the first 6 months in 3 political committees.

Trump has said he remains focused on Republicans winning back the House and Senate and has only teased another run by saying “you’ll be happy” with whatever he decides. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
The Supreme Court, by 5 to 4, declined Wednesday night to block Texas’s law banning abortions after six weeks. 

Hours later, top Republicans in Florida, Arkansas and South Dakota said they were examining how the law’s “private right of action” enforcement could be used for look-alike abortion bans in their own states.

The law could be struck down by courts long before the red state legislatures reconvene, if abortion rights groups can successfully show that people are being injured by the way the law cuts off access to the procedure. But that would require finding people willing to intentionally violate the ban and be plaintiffs in a challenge before the most conservative circuit court in the country and the Supreme Court’s conservative supermajority.

The Supreme Court could still strike down the Texas ban, with the conservative majority stressing it wasn’t ruling on the merits of the law when it turned away an emergency petition from abortion clinics to freeze the statute. But the question is whether the court essentially granted a grace period to a law that will cut off access to abortion in the state for weeks or months and invited lawmakers in other states to draft look-alike measures. Link in bio for more.

node.text:
"The majority” of special immigrant visa applicants were left in Afghanistan due in part to the complications of the evacuation, a State Department offical told reporters in a private briefing. 

The  official noted that there were many impediments to evacuating everyone who wanted out of Afghanistan, namely threats by ISIS-K, the fortified design of the airport, the Taliban’s “unpredictable” guarding at checkpoints, and viral communications among refugees.

While the administration did well evacuating over 120,000 people, the official argued, “everybody who lived it is haunted” by the evacuees the U.S. could not get out by the Aug. 31 deadline.

Some of those people include Afghan SIV applicants, who all worked alongside the U.S. during the 20-year war. While no estimate for the SIVs left behind is yet available, the official did say “it's the majority of them, just based on anecdotal information about the populations we were able to support.” Link in bio for more. 

📷: AP

node.text:
Sen. Joe Manchin urged Democrats to pause their effort to pass a $3.5 trillion social spending plan in an op-ed published Thursday in the Wall Street Journal. 

The West Virginia Democrat said that he wouldn't support the $3.5 trillion package “or anywhere near that level of additional spending” without further clarity on the economic impact of inflation and the national debt on current government programs. He argued that the pause is necessary to evaluate the pandemic’s trajectory and examine inflation patterns. 

The op-ed comes as House and Senate Democrats are working through the August recess to finalize language for the social spending plan. House progressives want to keep the Senate-passed infrastructure legislation and the social spending plan linked, but moderates have expressed doubts about the $3.5 trillion plan and want to focus on passing the $550 billion infrastructure bill at the end of the month.

Manchin voted to advance a framework for the social spending package last month, despite his public concerns. Democrats will need his vote to pass the social spending plan in the evenly split Senate. Link in bio for more. 

📷: Getty

node.text:
After a bitterly divided Supreme Court declined to block Texas's new abortion ban 5-4, all four dissenting justices wrote their own dissents – a highly unusual move that seems intended to signal their outrage. 

The conservative majority – Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas, plus Trump nominees Amy Coney Barrett, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh – concede the Texas law may be unconstitutional, but that the abortion providers challenging the statute had not met the high bar needed to get relief in the early stages of a lawsuit. They cited “complex,” “novel” legal technicalities and insist constitutionality can still be reviewed later on.

But the four dissenters – Chief Justice John Roberts and the court’s three liberals Stephen Breyer, Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor – called the law clearly unconstitutional and blasted the majority for shirking their duty.

Link in bio to read the majority's opinion and the four dissents.

node.text:
The Supreme Court declined to block Texas's law banning abortions after six weeks – a strong but not final indication that the court will soon overturn Roe v. Wade. For now, this strips most women of the right to an abortion in America's second-largest state. 

The justices were bitterly divided in the 5-4 ruling: 
➡️ The conservative majority – Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas, plus Trump nominees Amy Coney Barrett, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh – concede the Texas law may be unconstitutional, but that the abortion providers challenging the statute had not met the high bar needed to get relief in the early stages of a lawsuit. They cited “complex,” “novel” legal technicalities and insist constitutionality can still be reviewed later on. 
➡️ Chief Justice John Roberts and the court’s three liberals (Stephen Breyer, Elena Kagan, Sonia Sotomayor) called the law clearly unconstitutional and blasted the majority for shirking their duty. All four of them wrote dissents, which is highly unusual and seems to be a sign of their outrage. 

So what's next? The court is expected to decide the fate of Roe v. Wade when they hear another major abortion case this fall over a Mississippi law that seeks to ban abortion after 15 weeks of pregnancy (Dobbs v. Jackson Women’s Health Organization). Expect a ruling to come next year.

Meanwhile, abortion rights supporters are worried about potential copycat laws in other states and are also calling on Congress to pass legislation to codify Roe v. Wade. But some Democrats admit that's unlikely to gain enough support in the evenly spilt 50-50 Senate. 

Link in bio for our legal correspondent's breakdown of the ruling and to read the majority's opinion and all four dissents.

node.text:
With two weeks of early voting left before the California recall election, Democrats are tracking a worrisome sign for Gov. Gavin Newsom and the party at large — the governor’s relative weakness with Latinos.

California is solidly Democratic, so it would take a near-total Democratic turnout collapse for Newsom to be recalled. But Latino voters across the country shifted incrementally toward Donald Trump in 2020. 

Now, polls suggest this once reliable and fast-growing voting bloc for Democrats is softening on Newsom. It’s a reminder that Latino support for Democrats is not a given.

If the trend holds, with even a small segment of the Latino electorate embracing the GOP, it may spell disaster for the Democratic Party — and not just in California this year. Link in bio for more.
